# CONSUMER CONNECTS TO CONSUMER-VALIDATOR — ABSOLUTE, NON-NEGOTIABLE RULE

## THE RULE

**A Consumer NEVER, EVER connects to the Provider of the same module.**

**The "provider" from a Consumer's perspective is ALWAYS a Consumer Validator.**

This is NOT a suggestion. This is NOT optional. This is an ABSOLUTE architectural rule.

## The Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    WRONG (FORBIDDEN)                    │
│                                                         │
│  swim-dnotam-consumer ──X──> swim-dnotam-provider       │
│  swim-ed254-consumer  ──X──> swim-ed254-provider        │
│                                                         │
│  NEVER. JAMAIS. NUNCA. NIEMALS. MAI.                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    CORRECT (ALWAYS)                      │
│                                                         │
│  swim-dnotam-consumer ────> dnotam-consumer-validator   │
│  swim-ed254-consumer  ────> ed254-consumer-validator    │
│                                                         │
│  ALWAYS. SEMPRE. TOUJOURS. IMMER. SIEMPRE.             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Why (the bicycle analogy)

A Consumer and a Provider are two distinct products that can be sold together or separately to the same client. Think of it like selling a bicycle and a bicycle repair shop to the same client — the client does not sell to themselves. A client can be a Consumer, a Provider, or both at the same time. But they will always be a Consumer *of someone else*, and a Provider *for someone else* — never of themselves.

## Why (technical)

The Consumer Validator simulates what a real external SWIM provider (EUROCONTROL/AISP) would expose:
- Its own **Artemis broker** (AMQP endpoint)
- Its own **Subscription Manager REST API** (mock or lightweight)
- Its own **event generator** (publishes test events)

The actual Provider (`swim-dnotam-provider`, `swim-ed254-provider`) is a SEPARATE service that publishes to its OWN Artemis for real downstream external consumers. It is NOT what our Consumer connects to.

## In Practice — Endpoint Mapping

| Consumer CR field | Points to |
|---|---|
| `amqpBrokerHost` | `{validator-name}-artemis-{namespace}.apps.{domain}` |
| `swimServiceBaseURL` / `subscriptionManager.url` | `https://{validator-name}-{namespace}.apps.{domain}` |

### DNOTAM Consumer Example
```yaml
providers:
  - providerId: "provider"
    subscriptionManager:
      url: "https://dnotam-consumer-validator-swim-external-provider.apps.ocp4.masales.cloud"
    amqpBroker:
      host: "dnotam-consumer-validator-artemis-swim-external-provider.apps.ocp4.masales.cloud"
```

### ED-254 Consumer Example
```yaml
consumer:
  config:
    swimServiceBaseURL: "https://ed254-consumer-validator-swim-external-provider.apps.ocp4.masales.cloud"
    amqpBrokerHost: "ed254-consumer-validator-artemis-swim-external-provider.apps.ocp4.masales.cloud"
```

## Checklist Before Creating Any Consumer Sample/CR

- [ ] Does `amqpBrokerHost` contain the word `validator`? If NO → STOP, it's WRONG.
- [ ] Does `swimServiceBaseURL` / `subscriptionManager.url` contain the word `validator`? If NO → STOP, it's WRONG.
- [ ] Does any URL point to a `provider` (not `consumer-validator`)? If YES → STOP, it's WRONG.

## NEVER FORGET THIS RULE. EVER.